      Anti-ESG
   =20
 =20
If you want to have exposure to oil companies, right now the market offers =
you two sorts of asset managers:=09Regular asset managers will buy stock in=
 oil companies. Some of them will be indexers (and buy stock in all the oil=
 companies), while others will be active managers (and try to buy stock in =
the oil companies that will go up); some will be fairly unengaged sharehold=
ers, while others will call up the oil companies and say things like =E2=80=
=9Cyou should try to make more money.=E2=80=9D=09ESG =E2=80=94=C2=A0environ=
mental, social, and governance =E2=80=94=C2=A0asset managers will also buy =
stock in oil companies, but then they will call up the oil companies and sa=
y =E2=80=9Chey you should try to pollute less.=E2=80=9D Some of them will b=
e indexers (and buy stock in all the oil companies), while others will do E=
SG screens and only buy stock in the oil companies that already pollute les=
s than average. (In theory, some could be concentrated activist ESG investo=
rs, buying stock in the oil companies that pollute=C2=A0more=C2=A0than aver=
age and trying hard to get them to stop, though that seems rare.)The market=
, however, lacks a third category. What if you want an asset manager who wi=
ll buy stock in oil companies and call them up and say =E2=80=9Chey you sho=
uld try to pollute more=E2=80=9D? That=E2=80=99s hard to find! The major ca=
tegories of asset manager are, as it were, =E2=80=9Cneutral=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D; =E2=80=9Canti-ESG=E2=80=9D is not yet a major catego=
ry. More than that, even the big neutral asset managers =E2=80=94=C2=A0big =
indexers with=C2=A0no explicit ESG mandates =E2=80=94=C2=A0tend to be inter=
ested in the systemic risks of their portfolio; often they  view climate ch=
ange as a systemic risk, and so they push the oil companies in their portfo=
lio to pollute less. If you want your oil companies to pollute more, there =
is no natural home for you.Well, that=E2=80=99s not quite true; there=C2=A0=
are=C2=A0anti-ESG fund managers, and while they all seem to manage tiny amo=
unts of capital they tend to get a lot of press. Here=E2=80=99s a new one:A=
n upstart financial firm backed by Peter Thiel and Bill Ackman has a messag=
e for American corporations: Focus on making money, not taking stands.Vivek=
 Ramaswamy, who made his fortune in pharmaceutical startups before writing =
a book last year called =E2=80=9CWoke, Inc.,=E2=80=9D says he has raised $2=
0 million to start a fund manager that would urge companies not to wade int=
o hot-button social or environmental issues. Mr. Thiel invested both person=
ally and through his Founders Fund, joined by Palantir Technologies Inc. co=
-founder Joe Lonsdale and other venture investors. =E2=80=A6The firm, calle=
d Strive, will be based far from Wall Street in Mr. Ramaswamy=E2=80=99s hom=
e state of Ohio. In an interview Monday, the 36-year-old dubbed his approac=
h =E2=80=9Cexcellence capitalism,=E2=80=9D focused on letting companies do =
what they do best=E2=80=94and nothing else=E2=80=94and inveighed against wh=
at he sees as a creeping liberal bias inside BlackRock Inc. and its peers, =
Vanguard Group and State Street Corp. , which he called an =E2=80=9Cideolog=
ical cartel.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6Mr. Ramaswamy=E2=80=99s project began under =
cover months ago, code-named =E2=80=9CWhitestone=E2=80=9D to capture its ai=
m of being the anti-Blackrock, people familiar with the matter said. It isn=
=E2=80=99t known what products it will offer, and it has a long way to go t=
o rival the combined market power of the financial giants it seeks to chall=
enge.Okay.
