</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess it is time to talk about algor=
ithmic stablecoins again. Terra, or UST,[1] is an algorithmic stablecoin wh=
ose price is maintained by an arbitrage=C2=A0relationship with another cryp=
tocurrency, Luna. One UST is supposed to be worth one US=C2=A0dollar, and o=
ne UST can always be exchanged for a floating quantity of Luna with a marke=
t value of $1. If a UST is trading at $0.99, you can buy it for $0.99 and t=
hen exchange it for $1 worth of Luna, making an instant profit. If it is tr=
ading at $1.01, you can buy $1 worth of Luna (for $1) and use it to buy a U=
ST worth $1.01, making an instant profit. Because of this arbitrage relatio=
nship, while the price of Luna can fluctuate, the price of Terra should alw=
ays be $1: If it trades above or below $1, people will exchange Terra for L=
una or Luna for Terra until the price of Terra gets back to $1.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When we <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/27665525.278609/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2Fy=
dGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMTkvdGhlLXN0YWJpbGl0eS1vZi1hbGdvcml0aG1pYy1zdGFibGVjb2l=
ucz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTEwMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2=
U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA1MTAmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cBdc6d55de" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked about Terra last month</a>, I=
 wrote:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On first principles thi=
s is insane. It relies on [Luna] always being worth <em>something</em>. If =
[Luna]=C2=A0trades at $0.01, you can print 10 million of them and buy 100,0=
00 [Terra]=C2=A0and push the price up. But if [Luna] trades at $0.00, you c=
an print infinity quadrillion of them and you=E2=80=99re still not gonna be=
 able to push up the price of [Terra]. If [Luna] is worthless, it cannot be=
 used to support the price of [Terra]. And because <em>you just made it up<=
/em>, there is no particular reason for [Luna] to be worth anything, so the=
re is no particular reason for [Terra] to be worth a dollar. If <em>I</em> =
made up [Luna] and [Terra]=C2=A0on my computer and said to you =E2=80=9CI w=
ill give you the number 10 billion in this Excel spreadsheet if you give me=
 1 million U.S. dollars,=E2=80=9D you would say no, and if I raised my offe=
r to 400 quadrillion you would not change your mind.</p></blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nonetheless! It works? The rough intuition here is t=
hat there is a lot of demand for stablecoins; there is particularly a lot o=
f demand for Terra because Terraform Labs, the entity that created Luna and=
 Terra, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27665525.2=
78609/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9qb253dV8vc3RhdHVzLzE1MjM3OTM1MDA1MDgwOTQ0N=
jU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcfd6181b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">essentially pays</a> 19.5% <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27665525.278609/aHR0=
cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9hbmNob3JfcHJvdG9jb2wvc3RhdHVzLzE1MDQ5MjE2NzQ1NzkyNzk=
4NzM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1f0adc1e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">promotional interest</a> on=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27665525.278609/a=
HR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9HZW9yZ2VTZWxnaW4vc3RhdHVzLzE1MDk2MTYyNjM5MTk4MDg1=
MTg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB42207dc4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">UST deposits</a>. People wan=
t a stablecoin that is worth a dollar, so they are inclined to treat Terra =
as though it=E2=80=99s worth a dollar, which makes it worth a dollar. They =
buy lots of Luna to turn into Terra, which means that the price of Luna goe=
s up, which means that there is plenty of valuable Luna to support the pric=
e of Terra, which means that Terra is robustly worth a dollar.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ha, well, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/27665525.278609/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydG=
ljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMTAvY3J5cHRvLXMtYXVkYWNpb3VzLWFsZ29yaXRobWljLXN0YWJsZWNva=
W4tZXhwZXJpbWVudC1jcnVtYmxlcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTEwMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVk=
aXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA1MTAmdXRtX2NhbXB=
haWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf4b61360" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">oops</a>:</=
p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Rather than trading at $1, as de=
signed, the TerraUSD coin, or UST, slipped over the weekend to around 99 ce=
nts. By Monday evening in New York, it had plunged to 60 cents, obliteratin=
g its previous low of 92 cents in May 2021. It clawed back losses on Tuesda=
y and is fluctuating between around 90 cents and $1 -- =C2=A0a sign of trou=
ble. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are around 18.5 billio=
n of UST in circulation, according to CoinMarketCap, a big enough presence =
that its swings could have systemic implications for other coins and protoc=
ols. And Do Kwon, the crypto upstart behind UST, has previously committed t=
o buying as much as $10 billion worth of Bitcoin as part of his support of =
the coin, further entwining the project with the core of the digital-asset =
market. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That led to a series of crypto =
market interventions from Kwon and the so-called council of the Luna Founda=
tion Guard (LFG), a consortium of crypto players that includes Kanav Kariya=
 of Jump Crypto. Jump Crypto declined to comment. Near midnight New York ti=
me on Monday, UST remained under pressure. Luna was trading around $29, dow=
n 52% from a day earlier, according to CoinMarketCap.</p></blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/27665525.278609/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzL=
zIwMjItMDUtMDkvdGVycmEtc3RhYmxlY29pbi1iYWNrZXItdG8tbGVuZC10b2tlbnMtYWZ0ZXIt=
bG9zaW5nLWRvbGxhci1saW5rP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MTAyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW0=
9ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDUxMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ2=
49bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa312ff98" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> And</a>:</p><b=
lockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The declines spurred backers led by =
Do Kwon, the founder of Terraform Labs -- which powers the Terra blockchain=
 -- to issue $1.5 billion in loans denominated in both UST and Bitcoin to h=
elp support the digital currency.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">The basic thing that makes Terra valuable is=C2=A0<em>confidence =
in it</em>. The essential source of this confidence is ... just sort of rec=
ursive social belief? If you think that everyone else will treat Terra as w=
orth a dollar, then you will treat it as worth a dollar, and you won=E2=80=
=99t sell it for $0.90 in a panic, which means that it won=E2=80=99t go dow=
n to $0.90, etc. But if you think that everyone else will treat Terra as wo=
rth zero, then you will dump it as fast as you can at whatever price you ca=
n get, which means that it will go down below $0.90, etc.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Also there is an algorithm, but it is a <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27665525.278609/aHR0cHM6Ly9taXJyb3IueH=
l6L2RhbXNvbmRhby5ldGgvT1ZlQnJtcmZjV203dUtMbEEyUTRXMVhUVmtGVTNjTUtmTldoZ2Y3b=
VF1TQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc247c704" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">complicated cloak thrown=
 over these basic social facts</a>.=C2=A0If one Terra goes down to $0.90, t=
he arbitrage mechanism =E2=80=94=C2=A0you exchange one Terra for $1 worth o=
f Luna, and then sell your Luna into the market for $1 =E2=80=94 just doesn=
=E2=80=99t work. You exchange one Terra for $1 of Luna, but confidence in L=
una is also falling, and the market is being flooded with Luna as people tr=
y to do this arbitrage. So the $1 worth of Luna you received is no longer w=
orth $1, and then the next person who redeems Terra gets even more Luna and=
 has to sell even more of them, which drives the price down more, which inc=
reases the amount of Luna being issued, etc., in a =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27665525.278609/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMTcvdGl0YW5pdW0tZ290LWNy=
dXNoZWQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUxMDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc29=
1cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNTEwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3c818495" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">death spiral</a>.=E2=80=9D There =
is no particular floor on this process, and it can go until everything is w=
orth zero.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">However! As we discussed l=
ast month, Kwon and the Luna Foundation Guard did a smart thing. During the=
 virtuous cycle of Terra=E2=80=99s existence, as its market capitalization =
grew and as Luna became more valuable, they used their valuable Luna to buy=
 a bunch of Bitcoins. Luna is a creature of Terraform: If you lose confiden=
ce in Terra you will simultaneously lose confidence in Luna, and being able=
 to exchange one Terra for infinity bazillion Luna will not do anything to =
prop up the price of Terra. But <em>Bitcoin </em>is an entirely separate th=
ing. Terraform made up Terra and Luna, but somebody else made up Bitcoin. I=
f people lose confidence in Luna and Terra, Bitcoin will still be valuable.=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so the LFG bought a bunch of Bitcoin a=
nd promised to use it to defend Terra=E2=80=99s peg to the dollar. If one T=
erra goes down to $0.90, instead of turning Terra into Luna and selling the=
m in a death spiral, the LFG can buy Terra for $0.90 and pay for it in Bitc=
oin. If the LFG has enough Bitcoin, and if Bitcoin=E2=80=99s price holds up=
, then it can defend the peg and keep the price of Terra close to $1.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The point is that you print a lot of Luna when L=
una prices are high=C2=A0and exchange them for Bitcoin. And then if Luna pr=
ices fall, you can use the Bitcoin to buy Terra and keep it at $1, avoiding=
 a death spiral. As I wrote last month: =E2=80=9CThe basic structure of the=
 trade is (1) Ponzi, (2) acceptance, (3) diversification, (4) permanence.=
=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose Kwon would have liked a=
 few more months of widespread acceptance of Terra, so he could build up th=
e Bitcoin reserves. (=E2=80=9CWe will keep growing reserves until it become=
s mathematically impossible for idiots to claim depeg risk for $UST,=E2=80=
=9D Kwon <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27665525.=
278609/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9zdGFibGVrd29uL3N0YXR1cy8xNTAyMjI2MzIwOTg5=
NzAwMDk3/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0d9e28dc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">tweeted in March</a>; t=
he target was $10 billion of Bitcoin.) But he bought a=C2=A0<em>lot=C2=A0</=
em>of Bitcoin, anyway, which gave him a lot of ammunition to use to defend =
Terra=E2=80=99s peg when it broke over the last few days.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">So far it is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0working =E2=80=A6=C2=A0okay? As =
of noon today,=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/27665525.278609/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb2lubWFya2V0Y2FwLmNvbS9jdXJyZW5jaWVzL3RlcnJhd=
XNkLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc3ccf990" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">CoinMarketCap tells me</=
a> that Terra is at about $0.91, which is simultaneously (1) quite a lot lo=
wer than $1 but also (2) quite a lot higher than $0.=C2=A0Those are the two=
 stable equilibria of an algorithmic stablecoin: In the long run, either it=
=E2=80=99s worth a dollar or it=E2=80=99s worthless. Terra is still fightin=
g it out: It broke the buck (bad), but it does not seem to be in a death sp=
iral (good). Either Kwon, LFG and other Terra bulls will defend the peg and=
 wrestle it back to $1, or, uh, well, or they won=E2=80=99t and it will go =
to the other place.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As of right now I don=
=E2=80=99t know what the answer is and wouldn=E2=80=99t want to hazard a gu=
ess, though I will say that $0.91 is much closer to $1 than it is to $0. =
=E2=80=9CDeploying more capital - steady lads,=E2=80=9D Kwon <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27665525.278609/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0=
dGVyLmNvbS9zdGFibGVrd29uL3N0YXR1cy8xNTIzNzMzNTQyNDkyMDE2NjQw/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBded782c8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">tweeted yesterday</a>.=C2=A0I bet he=E2=80=99=
s having fun. =E2=80=9CClose to announcing a recovery plan for $UST. Hang t=
ight,=E2=80=9D he <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
27665525.278609/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9zdGFibGVrd29uL3N0YXR1cy8xNTI0MDQ=
5Njg5NTEwNjk0OTE2/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3acbff43" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">tweeted this m=
orning</a>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People often talk about =E2=80=
=9Cbank runs=E2=80=9D on stablecoins.=C2=A0Here, for instance, is the Feder=
al Reserve=E2=80=99s annual <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/27665525.278609/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZmVkZXJhbHJlc2VydmUuZ292L3B1YmxpY=
2F0aW9ucy9maWxlcy9maW5hbmNpYWwtc3RhYmlsaXR5LXJlcG9ydC0yMDIyMDUwOS5wZGY/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB53275473" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Financial Stability Report</a>, rele=
ased yesterday, which contains some worrying about run risk on stablecoins:=
</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Stablecoins typically aim to b=
e convertible, at par, to dollars, but they are backed by assets that may l=
ose value or become illiquid during stress; hence, they face redemption ris=
ks similar to those of prime and tax-exempt [money market funds]. These vul=
nerabilities may be exacerbated by a lack of transparency regarding the ris=
kiness and liquidity of assets backing stablecoins. Additionally, the incre=
asing use of stablecoins to meet margin requirements for levered trading in=
 other cryptocurrencies may amplify volatility in demand for stablecoins an=
d heighten redemption risks.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">T=
he idea of a bank run is that you have a=C2=A0<em>backed=C2=A0</em>stableco=
in, like Tether, in which each $1 stablecoin is in theory backed by at leas=
t $1 worth of dollar-denominated assets. The worry in a bank run is that pe=
ople all decide to withdraw their money from the stablecoin at once,=C2=A0p=
erhaps because they worry about its solvency (i.e., they worry that it is o=
nly backed by $0.99 of assets) or for some other reason. To meet withdrawal=
s, the stablecoin has to sell assets, which drives down their price, which =
leaves the coin backed only by, say, $0.95 worth of assets. Panicky holders=
 withdraw even more money, pushing the assets down more. And since holders =
get paid out at $1, they drain value out of the pool; people who don=E2=80=
=99t withdraw are left with claims on the bad illiquid assets, which are wo=
rth even less.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s not great, bu=
t what I want to emphasize is that=C2=A0<em>this is much worse</em>. A bank=
 run=C2=A0is a fairly mild event compared to a death spiral. In a bank run,=
 your $1 stablecoin is backed by=C2=A0some pool of assets that are worth so=
mething; a rush to withdraw money leads to fire sales that depress=C2=A0the=
ir value, but their value derives from something other than confidence in t=
he stablecoin. In a death spiral, the whole system is built on confidence i=
n the stablecoin; if that confidence evaporates then there is no floor at a=
ll on the value.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To put it another way: In =
the 2008 financial crisis, a money market fund called the Reserve Primary F=
und =E2=80=9Cbroke the buck=E2=80=9D; it had exposure to Lehman Brothers de=
bt, which defaulted, leading to a run on the fund and ultimately its liquid=
ation. This was huge news at the time, a seminal event of the global financ=
ial crisis. Also Reserve Primary Fund investors got back <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27665525.278609/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2Vj=
Lmdvdi9zcG90bGlnaHQvcmVzZXJ2ZV9wcmltYXJ5X2Z1bmRfaW52ZXN0b3JzL2dhcmRlcGhlX29=
waW5pb24ucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB85b860be" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">about 99 cents on =
the dollar</a>. The potential outcomes for a money market fund, or a fully =
backed stablecoin, are like (1) $1 or (2) slightly less than $1. That is no=
t how algorithmic stablecoins work.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhi=
le, the mechanism that LFG is using to defend the peg is interesting. It ha=
s=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27665525.27=
8609/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9sZmdfb3JnL3N0YXR1cy8xNTIzNTEyMjAxMDg4MTQzMz=
YwP3M9MTEmdD1QUmVNWnJqSTlfSDVfSE5fMTBSZmt3/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe39aa78=
6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"><em>loaned=C2=A0</em>Bitcoin</a> to market makers to use to pr=
otect the UST peg to the dollar. For one thing, this means that LFG (or, ra=
ther, the market makers) is effectively selling Bitcoin to buy UST, <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27665525.278609/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuY29pbmRlc2suY29tL3RlY2gvMjAyMi8wNS8xMC91c3Qtc3RhYmxlY29pbi12ZWVycy13=
aWxkbHktZnJvbS1kb2xsYXItcGVnLWhlcmVzLXRoZS1sYXRlc3Qv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cBf599c23e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">putting pressure on the price of=C2=A0<em>Bitcoin</em>=
</a>: If you are dumping Bitcoin to prop up the price of Terra, the price o=
f Bitcoin will go down.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a market=
 maker, presumably your bet here is that you can buy Terra at $0.91, it wil=
l stabilize, and you will end up being able to sell it in a few days for $1=
, making a quick 10% profit. Then I guess you buy back the Bitcoins you use=
d and deliver them back to LFG? You have some Bitcoin/dollar price risk; I =
suppose you can hedge that. The trade here is that $1 is a stable equilibri=
um for Terra, and if you can push it back to that equilibrium you=E2=80=99l=
l make a nice return on your efforts. You just need to make sure that you h=
ave enough capital to push it back to $1.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">B=
ecause the bad outcome is that this does not work, there is a death spiral,=
 and Terra ends up worthless. Then you wasted like a billion dollars of Bit=
coin buying something that was going to zero. That would be bad! Arguably L=
FG=E2=80=99s decision to deploy a lot of Bitcoin is a sign of confidence th=
at it will work. Otherwise they=E2=80=99d keep the Bitcoins.</p><table clas=
