</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Back in March, the US=C2=A0Securities =
and Exchange Commission <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/27665525.278609/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvM=
jAyMi01Ng/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB23309023" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">proposed new rules</a>=
 for special purpose acquisition companies. A SPAC is a blank-check company=
 that goes public, raises a pot of money, and then uses it to merge with so=
me private company, thus taking it public in a =E2=80=9Cde-SPAC transaction=
.=E2=80=9D There is a view that the target company can be more casual with =
its disclosure in the de-SPAC transaction than in a regular initial public =
offering. In a regular IPO, the company that is going public has to describ=
e its business accurately, with a focus on actual historical performance; i=
n a SPAC, the theory goes, the company can market itself based on wildly op=
timistic projections of future profits, and if it gets those projections wr=
ong no one gets in trouble.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC=E2=80=
=99s proposed rules crack down on that in various ways; we <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27665525.278609/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYm=
xvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMzEvdGhlLXNlYy1pcy1jb21pb=
mctZm9yLXNwYWNzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MTAyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwm=
dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDUxMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXl=
zdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB554c2474" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> discussed them in March=
</a>.=C2=A0One small odd element of the rules has to do with =E2=80=9Cunder=
writer liability.=E2=80=9D Basically if a bank underwrites an IPO, and the =
disclosure in the IPO is wrong, the bank can be sued. Similarly if a bank u=
nderwrites the initial offering of a SPAC, and the disclosure is wrong, the=
 bank can be sued =E2=80=94=C2=A0but SPACs are just empty boxes raising cas=
h, so there is not a lot of disclosure there to be wrong. Eventually the SP=
AC merges with a target company, and it puts out a disclosure document for =
that de-SPAC merger, describing the actual business of the target company (=
and its optimistic financial projections, etc.). But there is no =E2=80=9Cu=
nderwriter=E2=80=9D for the de-SPAC merger =E2=80=94=C2=A0the banks are not=
 technically selling stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0and so there is no underwriter li=
ability. So if the disclosure about the target company is wrong, it is hard=
 to sue the banks.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC proposed to chan=
ge this. Specifically, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/27665525.278609/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9ydWxlcy9wcm9wb3NlZC8yMDIyLz=
MzLTExMDQ4LnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfa59bf31" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the proposal sa=
ys</a>=C2=A0that=C2=A0if a bank=C2=A0<em>both=C2=A0</em>underwrites the ini=
tial public offering of the SPAC,=C2=A0<em>and=C2=A0</em>advises on the de-=
SPAC merger with the target company, then the bank will be liable for any m=
isstatements in the target company=E2=80=99s disclosure.[2] =E2=80=9CIn thi=
s way,=E2=80=9D says the SEC, the=C2=A0proposed rule =E2=80=9Cunderscores a=
nd reinforces that the liability protections in de-SPAC transactions involv=
ing registered offerings have the same effect as those in underwritten init=
ial public offerings.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What does th=
is rule mean? The SEC suggests that it will make underwriters more careful =
gatekeepers of de-SPAC transactions:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">The due diligence efforts performed by underwriters are central to th=
e integrity of our disclosure system. The investing public relies on underw=
riters to =E2=80=9Cscreen the multitude of issuers seeking access to the ca=
pital markets=E2=80=9D and expects them to verify the accuracy of the infor=
mation in the registration statement. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0The Commission has sta=
ted that =E2=80=9Can underwriter [in a securities offering] impliedly repre=
sents that he has made such an investigation [of the accuracy of the inform=
ation in the registration statement] in accordance with professional standa=
rds=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9C[i]nvestors properly rely on this=C2=A0added prot=
ection which has a direct bearing on their appraisal of the reliability of =
the representations in the prospectus.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">But there is an alternative interpretation of what the ru=
le means, which is: If you are a SPAC, you need to hire one bank to do the =
SPAC=E2=80=99s initial public offering, and a <em>different </em>bank to do=
 the de-SPAC merger. As long as one bank doesn=E2=80=99t do=C2=A0<em>both=
=C2=A0</em>things, then=C2=A0<em>neither=C2=A0</em>has any underwriter liab=
ility. It=E2=80=99s a bit more complicated than that =E2=80=94=C2=A0typical=
 SPAC underwriting fees are paid partly up front and partly on the de-SPAC =
merger, and getting those back-end fees can trigger underwriter liability, =
so you have to fiddle with the economics a bit =E2=80=94=C2=A0but that is t=
he basic idea. The SEC has created a nice new program to make companies hir=
e an extra bank for their SPAC deals.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anywa=
y here is a story titled =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/27665525.278609/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2F=
ydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMTAvZ2xvYmFsLWJhbmtzLWZsZWUtdGhlLW1vbnN0ZXItc3BhYy1tYX=
JrZXQtdGhleS1oZWxwZWQtY3JlYXRlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MTAyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZ=
WRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDUxMCZ1dG1fY2Ft=
cGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4d5e1b41" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Global Ba=
nks Flee the Monster SPAC Market They Helped Create</a>=E2=80=9D:</p><block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Just a few years after banks helped crea=
te a gargantuan market for blank-check companies, they=E2=80=99re pulling a=
way from the deals, afraid of the risks.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">Goldman Sachs Group Inc. is ending its involvement with most of the spe=
cial purpose acquisition companies it took public and pausing new U.S. SPAC=
 issuance, Bloomberg reported on Monday. Bank of America Corp. scaled back =
work with some SPACs and could retreat further as it evaluates its policies=
 surrounding the deals, people familiar with the matter said. =E2=80=A6</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The banks=E2=80=99 recent concerns center arou=
nd liability risks stemming from the new rules, which are aimed at tighteni=
ng oversight on a market after it set back-to-back yearly records. The prop=
osals would require SPACs to disclose more information about potential conf=
licts of interest and make it easier for investors to sue over false projec=
tions. =C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They also would require under=
writers of a blank-check offering to also be underwriters of the SPAC=E2=80=
=99s subsequent purchase of a target firm, known as the de-SPAC. That expan=
sion of underwriter liability poses a greater risk for investment banks, pr=
ominent law firms have cautioned.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">Well. They are fleeing the SPACs they created. But in theory Goldman co=
uld go do the mergers for Bank of America=E2=80=99s SPACs, and BofA could d=
o the mergers for Goldman=E2=80=99s SPACs, and everyone could get paid and =
no one would have underwriter liability. The SPAC market is not exactly boo=
ming right now, but if it comes back I suspect that the result of the SEC r=
ules will be a division of labor among SPAC-issuance banks and SPAC-merger =
banks. I am not sure how that helps anyone, except maybe the banks.</p><tab=
