</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you want to have exposure to oil co=
mpanies, right now the market offers you two sorts of asset managers:</p><o=
l style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Regular asset managers will buy stock =
in oil companies. Some of them will be indexers (and buy stock in all the o=
il companies), while others will be active managers (and try to buy stock i=
n the oil companies that will go up); some will be fairly unengaged shareho=
lders, while others will call up the oil companies and say things like =E2=
=80=9Cyou should try to make more money.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">ESG =E2=80=94=C2=A0environmental, social, and governance =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0asset managers will also buy stock in oil companies, but the=
n they will call up the oil companies and say =E2=80=9Chey you should try t=
o pollute less.=E2=80=9D Some of them will be indexers (and buy stock in al=
l the oil companies), while others will do ESG screens and only buy stock i=
n the oil companies that already pollute less than average. (In theory, som=
e could be concentrated activist ESG investors, buying stock in the oil com=
panies that pollute=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>than average and trying hard to=
 get them to stop, though that seems rare.)</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">The market, however, lacks a third category. What if you want an ass=
et manager who will buy stock in oil companies and call them up and say =E2=
=80=9Chey you should try to pollute <em>more</em>=E2=80=9D? That=E2=80=99s =
hard to find! The major categories of asset manager are, as it were, =E2=80=
=9Cneutral=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D; =E2=80=9Canti-ESG=E2=80=9D i=
s not yet a major category. More than that, even the big neutral asset mana=
gers =E2=80=94=C2=A0big indexers with=C2=A0no explicit ESG mandates =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0tend to be interested in the systemic risks of their portfolio; of=
ten they <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27665525.=
278609/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDEt=
MTQvYmxhY2tyb2NrLWhhcy1ncmVlbi1wbGFucz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTEwMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ=
1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA1MTAmdX=
RtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9deb85d0" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 view climate change as a systemic risk</a>, and so they push the oil compa=
nies in their portfolio to pollute less. If you want your oil companies to =
pollute more, there is no natural home for you.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">Well, that=E2=80=99s not quite true; there=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>anti=
-ESG fund managers, and while they all seem to manage tiny amounts of capit=
