=E2=80=99s a new one</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An up=
start financial firm backed by Peter Thiel and Bill Ackman has a message fo=
r American corporations: Focus on making money, not taking stands.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Vivek Ramaswamy, who made his fortune in pharmaceut=
ical startups before writing a book last year called =E2=80=9CWoke, Inc.,=
=E2=80=9D says he has raised $20 million to start a fund manager that would=
 urge companies not to wade into hot-button social or environmental issues.=
 Mr. Thiel invested both personally and through his Founders Fund, joined b=
y Palantir Technologies Inc. co-founder Joe Lonsdale and other venture inve=
stors. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The firm, called Strive, w=
ill be based far from Wall Street in Mr. Ramaswamy=E2=80=99s home state of =
Ohio. In an interview Monday, the 36-year-old dubbed his approach =E2=80=9C=
excellence capitalism,=E2=80=9D focused on letting companies do what they d=
o best=E2=80=94and nothing else=E2=80=94and inveighed against what he sees =
as a creeping liberal bias inside BlackRock Inc. and its peers, Vanguard Gr=
oup and State Street Corp. , which he called an =E2=80=9Cideological cartel=
.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mr. Ramaswamy=E2=80=99=
s project began under cover months ago, code-named =E2=80=9CWhitestone=E2=
=80=9D to capture its aim of being the anti-Blackrock, people familiar with=
 the matter said. It isn=E2=80=99t known what products it will offer, and i=
t has a long way to go to rival the combined market power of the financial =
giants it seeks to challenge.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
